Fact: Fossil evidence indicates citrus first evolved in the Himalayan foothills.
Citron was one of the first citrus fruits to be domesticated in India.
Citron was introduced to Greece and the Mediterranean through Persian traders.
Jews brought citron from Jerusalem to Calabria.
South Calabria and East Sicily are annexed by the Roman Empire.
Lemon cultivation begins in the Middle East during the Islamic Golden Age.
Arabs invade Sicily and bring sour orange and lemon trees.
Arabs invade Sicily and bring sour orange and lemon trees.
Normans conquest of Sicily.

Fact Light: Famous lemon variety grown in Salerno
Fact: Limone Femminello Sfusato Amalfitano emerges on the coast of the Bay of Salerno.
Crusaders brought a sweeter orange back to Europe from Jerusalem.

Fact Light: The Battle of Oranges marks rebellion
Fact: "Battle of Oranges" rebellion in Ivrea involves symbolic citrus fruit.
Franciscan friars introduce lemons to the shores of Lake Garda.

Fact Light: Charles I of Anjou invades Sicily
Fact: Charles I of Anjou invades Sicily.

Fact Light: Sicilian Vespers leads to a regime change
Fact: The Sicilian Vespers overthrow Charles I of Anjou, and Peter of Aragon becomes king.
Citrus seeds were brought to the Americas by Christopher Columbus on his second voyage.
Calabria comes under Spanish rule as part of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.

Fact Light: Vasco da Gama brings sweet oranges to Europe
Fact: Vasco da Gama brings back sweet oranges after discovering the Cape of Good Hope.
A sailor returning from Vietnam introduces the first Chinotto to Italy via Savona.

Fact Light: Cosimo de' Medici commissions citrus garden
Fact: Cosimo de' Medici commissions a citrus garden for Castello in Florence, housing citrus.

Fact Light: Sweet oranges arrive in Italy from China
Fact: The first truly sweet oranges reach Italy from China.
The first bergamot trees appear in Calabria due to natural cross-pollination.
Spanish settlers establish orange groves in Florida, laying the foundation for U.S. citrus farming.

Fact Light: Bizzarria, a citrus chimera, is discovered
Fact: A rare chimera citrus variety, Bizzarria, is found growing in a garden in Florence.
Giovanni Battista Ferrari publishes Hesperides, a taxonomy of citrus fruits.

Fact Light: Bartolomeo Bimbi begins painting Tuscan fruits
Fact: Bartolomeo Bimbi starts work on paintings of every kind of fruit growing in Tuscany.
Pomelo becomes widely cultivated in Southeast Asia.

Giovanni Maria Farina invents a bergamot-based perfume and names it Eau de Cologne. «Il mio profumo è come un mattino italiano di primavera dopo la pioggia: ricorda le arance, i limoni, i pompelmi, i bergamotti, i cedri, i fiori e le erbe aromatiche della mia terra. Mi rinfresca e stimola sensi e fantasia»

Fact Light: Medici citrus collection acquired by Francis I
Fact: Francis I, Duke of Lorraine, acquires the Medici citrus collection.
Carl Nilsson Linnaeus includes citrus in his international system of plant nomenclature.
Bergamot begins to be grown on a commercial scale in Calabria.
James Lind’s Treatise of the Scurvy (Lind 1753) undertakes the first controlled trial of lemon juice in the treatment of scurvy.

Fact Light: Medici citrus collection inherited by Pietro Leopoldo
Fact: Pietro Leopoldo, Duke of Lorraine, inherits the Medici citrus collection.
The opening of Florence's natural history museum, La Specola.

Fact Light: Lemons grown commercially during Napoleon's invasion
Fact: Lemons are commercially grown on the shores of Lake Garda while Napoleon invades northern Italy.
Satsuma mandarins, native to Japan, spread to Europe and North America.

Fact Light: Malta supplies lemon juice to the British Navy
Fact: The Admiralty appoints Sicily and Malta as sole suppliers of lemon juice to the British Navy worldwide.

Fact Light: British merchants invest in Sicilian citrus
Fact: Sicily is under British administration, attracting British merchants to the citrus industry.

Fact Light: First lemons exported to the United States
Fact: The first lemons are exported to the United States.
Giorgio Gallesio publishes Traité du Citrus, advancing citrus classification.

Fact Light: First mandarin recorded in Palermo botanical garden
Fact: Mandarins are first recorded on Italian soil in the Palermo Botanical Garden inventory.

Fact Light: Bergamot oil used in Earl Grey tea
Fact: Earl Grey received a gift of tea flavored with bergamot oil from a grateful Chinese mandarin.

Fact Light: America drops duty on Italian citrus
Fact: America drops the excise duty on Italian citrus, increasing exports dramatically.
Società di Lago di Garda is set up to protect lemon producers from unscrupulous middlemen.
The first mandarin glut occurs in Sicily.
Nicola Brilla invents the Macchina Calabrese, a revolutionary machine for extracting bergamot essential oil.

Fact Light: Garibaldi frees Sicily; mafia emerges in lemon trade
Fact: Garibaldi lands in Sicily, freeing the island from Bourbon rule. Mafia-like activity grows in Conca d’Oro’s lemon gardens.

Fact Light: British Navy switches to Caribbean lime suppliers
Fact: The Admiralty stops using Sicilian lemons and contracts West Indies suppliers for the entire Navy.
Augusto Besio opens a factory in Liguria for candying citrus fruit.

Fact Light: Steamship exports Sicilian citrus to the USA
Fact: A steamship is used for the first time to export citrus fruit from Sicily to America.

Fact Light: Amalfi lemon yields increased by irrigation changes
Fact: Water is withheld from Femminello lemons, forcing them to fruit in August for the first time.

Fact Light: Study links lemon trade and criminal activity
Fact: Leopoldo Franchetti and Sidney Sonnino investigate Sicilian society, connecting crime with the lemon trade.

Fact Light: WWI halts Lake Garda's lemon production
Fact: WWI leads to the abandonment of lemon houses on Lake Garda; Medici citrus collection is ousted from Castello’s Limonaia.
American chemist James Currie discovers citric acid can be made by feeding glucose to Aspergillus niger mold.
The Gardesena Road is built, and San Pellegrino invents Chinotto.

Fact Light: Vitamin C identified in lemon juice
Fact: Albert Szent-Györgyi wins the Nobel Prize for identifying Vitamin C as the antiscorbutic ingredient in lemon juice.

Fact Light: Valuable late mandarins first grown in Ciaculli
Fact: Avana mandarin trees mutate, producing the first valuable crop of late-maturing mandarini tardivi di Ciaculli.

Fact Light: Frost devastates Ligurian citrus, Calabrian renaming
Fact: Severe frost kills most Ligurian citrus trees; Cipollina is renamed Santa Maria del Cedro for its citron fields.

Fact Light: Mandarins linked to heroin trade in Sicily
Fact: Nixon’s war on drugs redirects heroin refineries to Sicily, beneath Greco family mandarin groves near Palermo.
Carlo Petrini founds the Slow Food movement, later protecting Chinotto and Mandarini Tardivi di Ciaculli.

Fact Light: Project Life restores Ciaculli mandarin groves
Fact: Project Life rejuvenates Ciaculli mandarin production.

Fact Light: Calabrian bergamot oil earns DOP status
Fact: Genuine Calabrian bergamot oil receives Denominazione di Origine Protetta (DOP) certification.
Leoluca Orlando resigns as Palermo mayor, leading to Project Life's collapse.

Fact Light: Chinotto chosen as symbol of Savona
Fact: The Chinotto is selected as a symbol of the city of Savona.

Fact Light: Chinotto receives Slow Food presidio nomination
Fact: Chinotto is nominated for a presidio within the Slow Food movement to protect endangered traditional products.
Bergamot production in Calabria sees a resurgence due to increased demand for essential oils and the global perfume industry.

Fact Light: Rise of genetically engineered citrus varieties
Fact: Genetically engineered citrus trees resistant to diseases like citrus greening begin to be tested and planted in various countries.
China becomes the world's largest producer of citrus fruits, particularly oranges and mandarins.
Increasing temperatures and drought in the Mediterranean lead to decreased citrus yields and shifts in farming practices.
The COVID-19 pandemic increases demand for bergamot essential oil due to its therapeutic properties and its use in aromatherapy products.
Brazilian farms adopt eco-friendly practices to counter deforestation and improve sustainability in orange cultivation.
New hybrid varieties with enhanced resistance to diseases and pests are developed, ensuring the future sustainability of citrus farming.
